      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While some very minor reactions might start at lower temperatures, the Maillard reaction needs a certain amount of thermal energy to proceed at a noticeable rate. This higher temperature range is crucial because the breaking and reforming of chemical bonds between the amino acids and sugars requires sufficient kinetic energy. If it's too cool, the reaction is too slow; it's the heat that drives the chemical transformation into those flavorful melanoidins that cause the browning.",
