    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i get the kinetic energy part. what happens if it gets WAY hotter than that though? like if i leave the pan on too long, it stops being \"flavorful melanoidins\" and just turns black/burnt. is that still the same reaction or something else entirely?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you go significantly hotter, like letting something burn, you are entering a different chemical territory, which is mostly caramelization and pyrolysis. Caramelization is the breakdown of sugars themselves, independent of amino acids, which also leads to browning, but it's a separate pathway. Pyrolysis is the thermal decomposition of organic matter, which is essentially burning, and produces bitter, acrid compounds. So, while both are heat-related browning, burning is a destructive process, not a flavorful one.",
